### Decision 2 — The consistency guard: new check (g) in the audit script

Add a new check **(g) retro subject consistency** to
`scripts/dogfood-completeness-audit.sh`, modeled on existing checks (c)/(f) which
already iterate `refs/etude/retros/*`, filter `refs.trigger=="cadence-retro"`, and
read manifests via `git cat-file -p <ref>:manifest.json` (audit.sh:368-398, 435-530).
**Batch modes only** (`--last`/`--since`), NOT `--bead` — consistent with (c)/(f),
which skip `--bead` to avoid close-time deadlocks (the guard is repo-wide advisory).

**Verdict: WARN, not BLOCK.** Rationale:
- Consistency is advisory and the signal is a *body-text parser* over human-written
  titles. A brittle parser must NEVER hard-fail a code push. (c) and (f)-pre-cutoff
  are both WARN-only for the same "advisory, don't deadlock" reason
  (audit.sh:357-416, 533-537).
- A clean "title-claims-X but X not in refs" case (exactly B16) is a real defect, but
  WARN surfaces it loudly in batch output without blocking unrelated pushes. After the
  B16 repair lands, the corpus is clean and the WARN is silent — so a future
  regression (a new cadence retro whose body claims a subject it didn't `--subject-run`
  /`--bead`) shows up immediately as the ONLY WARN. Promoting to BLOCK can be a
  follow-up once the parser has proven non-brittle in practice; do NOT BLOCK on a
  body-parser in its first iteration.

**Parse method (where-possible; the body title, not the manifest):**
- The manifest does NOT carry the title; the subject id-list lives in the retro BODY's
  first heading line. So read the body: find the stage with `output.role=="retro"`,
  take its `output.path`, `git cat-file -p <ref>:<path>`, take line 1.
- Extract candidate ids from the LAST parenthetical group in the title, e.g.
  `(6j8/kig/nm6)`, `(094/21z/sb4 + 9ey defer)`, `(2ku/qih/aqt)`.
  Algorithm (validated against the live corpus, see Risks):
  1. Find all `(...)` groups; take the LAST one (subjects are trailing).
  2. Split that group on ` + ` and keep only the FIRST chunk — this DROPS
     "+ 9ey defer" / "+ 8b7 defer" (deferred beads named in B13/B15 titles, which are
     NOT subjects and correctly absent from refs).
  3. Require the chunk to contain `/` AND split into >=2 tokens.
  4. Require EVERY token to match the bead-id shape `^[a-z0-9]+(\.[a-z0-9]+)*$`.
     If any token fails (e.g. a date group `2026-05-25/26` -> token `2026-05-25` has
     hyphens), REJECT the whole group and treat the retro as "no parseable subjects"
     -> SKIP. This all-or-nothing rule is what prevents the date false positive.
  5. Prefix each surviving token with `etude-` to form the candidate id.
- For each candidate id, assert it appears in the manifest's subject keys
  (`subject_run.*` OR `bead.*` values). Any candidate NOT present -> one WARN per ref
  listing the missing ids.
- **"Where possible":** a retro whose title yields NO candidate id-list (workflow
  retros titled `... — commit <sha>`; B17 with no parenthetical id-list) is SKIPPED
  silently — there is nothing to compare. This is exactly how the 7 mis-tagged
  `retro-workflow-workflow-*` refs pass trivially (Decision 4).

**Allowlist for known exceptions:** reuse the existing
`scripts/dogfood-completeness-allow.txt` mechanism is NOT a good fit (it's keyed by
bead id, not retro ref). Instead, add a small inline allowlist constant in the script
keyed by retro ref id for any retro that legitimately diverges and cannot be repaired
(currently EMPTY — B16 is repaired, not allowlisted). Document the constant inline so
future genuine exceptions have a home. Keep it minimal; prefer repair over allowlist.

**Footgun avoidance:** do the title read + id parsing entirely inside a single
`python3 -c` block fed the manifest on stdin (like (c)/(f) at audit.sh:370-398), and
use Python set membership for the comparison. Do NOT use `grep -c ... || echo 0`
(the documented B17 regression, retro-ledger.md:482-485) — there is no grep-count
anywhere in this check.

