### Risks

- **Parser brittleness (the main risk):** human-written titles are not a schema. A
  corpus dry-run of the proposed parser caught a real false positive — the B5 workflow
  retro title `... (2026-05-25/26) — commits ...` made a naive `/`-split emit a bogus
  `etude-26` candidate. MITIGATED by the all-tokens-must-be-valid-id rule (step 4),
  which rejects the date group entirely; re-validated dry-run flags ONLY B16 and skips
  all workflow/date/no-id-list titles. WARN-not-BLOCK further contains residual risk:
  a future title the parser misreads at worst produces a noisy WARN, never a blocked
  push. The inline retro-ref allowlist absorbs any genuine un-repairable exception.
- **Double re-capture lineage:** the B16-corrected ref will be re-captured AGAIN by
  8hq.5 (to add the sidecar). Accepted and documented as honest history (Decision 1).
- **`--bead` vs `--subject-run` cadence coverage:** check (c) only counts
  `subject_run.*` as "covered" (audit.sh:378-385), so representing nm6 as `--bead`
  (not `--subject-run`) does not change nm6's cadence-coverage status — correct, since
  nm6 has no run to cover and is allowlisted anyway. No regression to (c).

